{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:34:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:34:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15727"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15727"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0,0.03,0.55,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62883"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8418"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48333"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1353"},{"type":"tags","id":"1627"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7037"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20274"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62883"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ovarian morphology in polycystic ovarian syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enlarged ovaries with multiple follicles","Small ovaries with few follicles","Normal sized ovaries with absent follicles","Small ovaries with multiple cysts","Normal sized ovaries with single dominant follicle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), the ovaries are typically \u003Cstrong\u003Eenlarged\u003C/strong\u003E and contain multiple small follicles arranged in a \u0027string of pearls\u0027 pattern around the periphery. This appearance results from arrested follicular development, where follicles fail to mature and ovulate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ovaries are not \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall\u003C/strong\u003E, as the accumulation of multiple follicles actually increases their size. It would be incorrect to say the ovaries have \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsent follicles\u003C/strong\u003E as increased follicle numbers is a defining characteristic. While \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple cysts\u003C/strong\u003E may sound similar, the structures seen are actually immature follicles rather than cysts. A \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle dominant follicle\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of normal ovulation, which does not occur regularly in PCOS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnostic criteria for polycystic ovaries on ultrasound include the presence of at least 12 follicles measuring 2-9mm in diameter per ovary, and/or increased ovarian volume greater than 10mL.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Polycystic ovarian syndrome is characterized by enlarged ovaries containing multiple small follicles","The increased number of follicles in PCOS results from arrested follicular development","Ultrasound findings show at least 12 follicles per ovary measuring 2-9mm in diameter"],"references":["Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Witchel SF, Oberfield SE, Pe\u00f1a AS. Polycystic Ovary Syndrome: Pathophysiology, Presentation, and Treatment With Emphasis on Adolescent Girls. J Endocr Soc. 2019 Jun 14;3(8):1545-1573. doi: 10.1210/js.2019-00078. PMID: 31384717; PMCID: PMC6676075","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Singh S, Pal N, Shubham S, Sarma DK, Verma V, Marotta F, Kumar M. Polycystic Ovary Syndrome: Etiology, Current Management, and Future Therapeutics. J Clin Med. 2023 Feb 11;12(4):1454. doi: 10.3390/jcm12041454. PMID: 36835989; PMCID: PMC9964744"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48333"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15727"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48333"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T08:26:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T08:27:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8418"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62883"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,